### 6. Found-but-not-fixed

**`??` null-guard elision**: The contract mentions `?? default` null guards. The `??` operator desugars in the checker to `{ val tmp = left; if (tmp != null) tmp else right }`. By the time this reaches lowering, `tmp` always has type `T | Null` (the checker errors if the left side is never null), so the `if (tmp != null)` guard is genuinely needed — there is no redundant null guard to elide for `??`. The "non-null" part of the contract is fully addressed by the `is T` optimization (proving the value's tag is known), which covers the union-tag dispatch half. No bug found, just the scope is narrower than the contract text implies.

**Coordinate note for RT.2b**: `lower/coerce.rs` (boxing/unboxing coercion lowering) is untouched. This change only modifies `lower/expr.rs` and `lower/match_.rs` at the `Is` instruction sites. No overlap.

### 7. Honest status

**DONE** — ready for orchestrator verification. The optimization is conservative (only fires when both types are fully concrete), correct (confirmed by `LIN_VERIFY_RC=1` test suite and manual ASan), and the LLVM IR evidence shows the targeted `is T` checks being elided to `br i1 true` exactly where the static types prove they're redundant.
